snippet.textDisplay:
Yeah, Nintendo has never really been a company that prioritizes high specifications for their consoles, and that is now becoming inconvenient for them. It does tend to mean that their consoles are cheaper to purchase compared to XBox and Playstation, but it also means that their game library often lacks games with higher graphical fidelity because the system literally can't handle them.

Worst part is that Nintendo is basically using a design from nVidia called the Jetson series of integrated computing platform and the Jetson AGX Xavier model of that platform has been available since 2018 with a 512 core Volta GPU with 48 tensor cores (which roughly translates to somewhere around the performance of a GTX 1050 mobile GPU, but with additional tensor cores). From what I can tell, most of the reason why Nintendo never bothered to try to upgrade to this platform from the original TX1 platform is due to the significantly higher TDP and power draw, which would necessitate that the device be bulkier to provide adequate cooling and battery capacity. Given how well the Steamdeck is doing despite being larger, thicker, and heavier, I suspect that Nintendo might be regretting those choices. It looks like they've ordered a custom chip from nVidia this time that is between Jetson Orin NX and Jetson AGX Orin. It has more CUDA cores than the NX, but not as many as the AGX, and the memory specifications are below the minimum for the AGX.
